The goal is to prove: `‚Äñeval (‚Üëq) (X - C lamb)‚Äñ ^ 2 = ‚Äñ‚Üëq - lamb‚Äñ ^ 2`.

Let's think about what `eval (‚Üëq) (X - C lamb)` means. In the polynomial ring `‚ÑÇ[X]`, the polynomial `X - C lamb` is evaluated at the complex number `‚Üëq` (which is `q` cast from `‚Ñï` to `‚ÑÇ`). So `eval (‚Üëq) (X - C lamb)` is the complex number `‚Üëq - lamb`.

Therefore, `‚Äñeval (‚Üëq) (X - C lamb)‚Äñ` is the norm of the complex number `‚Üëq - lamb`. The norm of a complex number `z = x + yi` is `‚àö(x¬≤ + y¬≤)`. So `‚Äñ‚Üëq - lamb‚Äñ` is `‚àö((q - a)¬≤ + b¬≤)`.

The left side of the equation is `‚Äñ‚Üëq - lamb‚Äñ ^ 2`, which is `(‚àö((q - a)¬≤ + b¬≤))¬≤ = (q - a)¬≤ + b¬≤`.
The right side is `‚Äñ‚Üëq - lamb‚Äñ ^ 2`, which is the same.

So the equality is trivially true by definition. Let's write the Lean proof:

