So `‚Äñ(X - (C lamb)).eval (q : ‚ÑÇ)‚Äñ` is `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ`.

The theorem states that `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ > q - 1`.

Now, `q` is a natural number, so `q ‚â• 0`. The norm `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ` is the complex modulus of the difference `q - lamb`.

Since `lamb` is a primitive root of order `n`, we know `lamb ‚âÝ 1` and `lamb^n = 1`. Also, `lamb` is on the unit circle, so `‚Äñlamb‚Äñ = 1`.

To prove `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ > q - 1`, we can use the triangle inequality. We know `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ ‚â• ‚Äñq‚Äñ - ‚Äñlamb‚Äñ`. Since `‚Äñlamb‚Äñ = 1`, this gives `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ ‚â• ‚Äñq‚Äñ - 1`.

Since `q` is a natural number, `‚Äñq‚Äñ = q` (as a complex number). So `‚Äñq - lamb‚Äñ ‚â• q - 1`.

